WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:06.040
What if I told you that every choice you've ever made, you know, every job you turned down,

00:06.200 --> 00:14.200
every person you loved, or every agonizing mistake you deeply regret has literally been

00:14.200 --> 00:19.140
erased from the universe? It's a pretty intense thought, right? It's terrifying. But I don't just

00:19.140 --> 00:23.400
mean forgotten by the people around you or fading into the background of your mind. I mean

00:23.400 --> 00:29.560
mathematically, physically, and just permanently deleted from existence. Yeah, mathematically,

00:29.560 --> 00:35.740
deleted. That's the crux of it. Exactly. So today on the deep dive, we are looking at this

00:35.740 --> 00:43.540
staggering new paper that basically proves your identity isn't this grand sweeping story of your

00:43.540 --> 00:49.080
life that you tell yourself. Right. Your identity is actually just the mathematical residue that's

00:49.080 --> 00:55.800
left behind after all your other possibilities collapse. It is an incredibly confronting premise

00:55.800 --> 01:02.680
to start with. But I mean, that is exactly where the math leads us. So the source material we're

01:02.680 --> 01:08.560
looking at today is a 2026 monograph by an independent researcher going by the name Fliction.

01:09.020 --> 01:14.700
Yeah. Titled Identity After Collapse, Self-Reference in Normal Form Fixed Points.

01:14.700 --> 01:24.280
Which sounds incredibly dense. And on the surface, it is this intensely theoretical piece of work.

01:24.420 --> 01:31.620
Oh, absolutely. It is grounded in the absolute bleeding edge of formal computation, logic, and

01:31.620 --> 01:37.460
philosophy. Right. But what makes it so important for you listening right now is that the core mechanism

01:37.460 --> 01:44.260
it describes applies to almost literally everything we experience. Yeah. Our mission for this deep dive

01:44.260 --> 01:50.920
is really to completely dismantle this massive invisible assumption we all just walk around with

01:50.920 --> 01:57.340
every single day. Which is this idea that computation, language, and logic are reversible processes.

01:57.720 --> 02:02.540
Right. Exactly. We tend to think of them like physical roads. You know, if you drive from point A to point B,

02:02.540 --> 02:07.060
you assume you can always just put the car in reverse and drive from point B back to point A.

02:07.140 --> 02:13.280
Like you can retrace your steps. Right. But Fliction just says absolutely not. The road disappears the exact

02:13.280 --> 02:20.640
moment you drive over it. The road is just gone. And from that destroyed road, the paper reconstructs a

02:20.640 --> 02:27.400
completely new understanding of what it actually means to have an identity. So the standard accounts of

02:27.400 --> 02:34.360
computation and, you know, by extension, how we think about causality and logic, they treat the evaluation

02:34.360 --> 02:41.160
of a problem as this simple mapping function. Like an input-output machine. Yeah. You input a state,

02:41.360 --> 02:48.000
the system processes it, and you get an output. But classical models treat the actual process connecting

02:48.000 --> 02:53.300
those two states as totally incidental. Like it doesn't really matter how you got there.

02:53.300 --> 02:57.760
Right. They assume that a perfect system would allow you to look at the final output

02:57.760 --> 03:03.480
and magically reconstruct the exact starting point and the path taken.

03:04.120 --> 03:07.780
But Fliction removes that assumption entirely, right?

03:08.040 --> 03:14.400
Completely. In this framework, evaluation isn't just a translation from one language to another.

03:14.860 --> 03:16.980
Evaluation is an act of total destruction.

03:17.580 --> 03:23.100
Okay. To really wrap our heads around this, because it gets incredibly deep philosophically,

03:23.300 --> 03:26.440
we need to start exactly where the paper starts.

03:26.580 --> 03:27.700
With some basic math.

03:27.820 --> 03:32.800
Yeah. Just a really simple math problem. Basic arithmetic. Because hidden right inside

03:32.800 --> 03:36.940
middle school math is this massive illusion we've all totally bought into.

03:37.220 --> 03:42.500
Right. So let's set up the example the paper uses. Just imagine a very basic equation written

03:42.500 --> 03:43.280
on a chalkboard.

03:43.320 --> 03:44.400
Okay. I'm picturing it.

03:44.400 --> 03:51.060
It's 8 plus, open parenthesis, 3 times 5, close parenthesis.

03:51.180 --> 03:58.140
Okay. So following the order of operations, you do the parenthesis first. So 3 times 5 is 15.

03:58.280 --> 03:58.960
Perfect. Yeah.

03:59.020 --> 04:04.140
And then you add the 8. So 8 plus 15 evaluates to 23.

04:04.400 --> 04:05.980
I mean, simple enough, right?

04:06.080 --> 04:06.660
Simple enough.

04:06.660 --> 04:15.380
The intact equation evaluates to the number 23. But here is the hinge of Flickshian's entire argument.

04:15.540 --> 04:16.420
Okay. Lay on me.

04:16.800 --> 04:21.660
From the number 23, you cannot reverse engineer that starting equation.

04:21.720 --> 04:28.520
Oh, right. Because 23 could be the result of a near infinite number of different starting conditions.

04:28.880 --> 04:29.240
Exactly.

04:29.240 --> 04:33.940
Like, it could be 20 plus 3. It could be 50 minus 27.

04:34.180 --> 04:36.960
Or 100 divided by 4 minus 2.

04:37.080 --> 04:45.040
Right. Multiple, completely distinct expressions all collapse into the exact same numerical value.

04:45.300 --> 04:51.340
And that collapses the point. You see, standard models of computation usually use something called

04:51.340 --> 04:53.040
abstract syntax trees.

04:53.520 --> 04:56.980
Abstract syntax trees. What are those?

04:56.980 --> 05:02.220
They map out the equation like a static family tree with nodes and branches.

05:03.020 --> 05:12.000
They treat the whole thing as this static geometric object, completely ignoring the flow of time and the actual process of calculation.

05:12.320 --> 05:20.920
So they just pretend that because 23 is the definitive answer, it somehow secretly encodes the truth of the original expression.

05:20.920 --> 05:26.160
Yes. But Flickshian points out that evaluation actually destroys information.

05:26.980 --> 05:33.720
The intermediate structural scaffolding that justified that final result is just gone.

05:33.920 --> 05:39.460
Wow. So the number 23 does not and mathematically cannot encode its own derivation.

05:39.660 --> 05:40.100
Exactly.

05:40.400 --> 05:43.580
It's like saying evaluation is essentially a process of elimination.

05:44.120 --> 05:46.100
It's not just solving a puzzle.

05:46.320 --> 05:49.640
No, it's actively burning the puzzle pieces in a fire as you go.

05:49.640 --> 05:55.780
Yeah. So that by the time you have the final picture, the cardboard pieces themselves literally no longer exist.

05:56.000 --> 06:06.640
That's a great way to put it. And to formalize this mathematical destruction, Flickshian introduces a brand new computational system called the SpherePop Calculus.

06:07.380 --> 06:09.880
SpherePop Calculus. I love that name.

06:10.140 --> 06:10.980
It's catchy, right?

06:10.980 --> 06:16.860
It is designed from the ground up to be an irreversible append-only system.

06:17.340 --> 06:19.560
So instead of those static trees we just mentioned.

06:19.820 --> 06:27.300
Instead of trees, SpherePop uses nested bubbles to represent bounded regions of structural commitment.

06:27.400 --> 06:33.280
Okay. Nested bubbles. Can you walk me through what a bubble actually looks like in this context?

06:33.480 --> 06:39.860
Sure. So in our math problem, the operation 3 times 5 is sitting inside a parenthesis, right?

06:39.860 --> 06:43.260
Yeah. In SpherePop, that parenthesis is a bubble.

06:44.260 --> 06:49.920
The nesting of these bubbles determines the scope of where local operations are allowed to happen.

06:50.060 --> 06:53.640
So the innermost bubble is like the first site of commitment.

06:54.000 --> 07:01.500
Exactly. And when a bubble pops, meaning when that 3 times 5 actually executes and evaluates to 15,

07:02.300 --> 07:04.700
its internal structure is entirely consumed.

07:05.420 --> 07:05.980
Presumed.

07:05.980 --> 07:09.540
Like deleted, permanently erased from the system's memory.

07:09.860 --> 07:14.360
The system does not maintain a ledger of the alternatives it didn't take.

07:14.460 --> 07:15.240
Oh, wow.

07:15.600 --> 07:18.740
